article.headline: Carter, Bosh sprain ankles
article.linkText: Duncan's boards lift Spurs past Raptors
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Tim Duncan and the San Antonio Spurs took advantage of Vince Carter's absence to post their sixth straight victory. Duncan scored 26 points and tied a season-high with 21 rebounds as the Spurs beat the Toronto Raptors 86-82 Wednesday night. Carter was helped off the court after injuring his left ankle with 7:46 left in the fourth quarter. The Toronto star rolled his ankle coming down on a jumper. He remained down for several minutes clutching the ankle before two teammates and the trainer helped him to the locker room. The Spurs went on a 12-1 run after he left. "When he went down, we took over from there," Duncan said. "They didn't have anybody to go to." Carter, who will undergo an MRI exam on Thursday, scored a team-high 22 points. Carter wondered if San Antonio's Bruce Bowen purposely tripped him up. "I question whether it was an accident or whether it was on purpose, because it's not very often where you see somebody put their foot right under you like that," Carter said. Carter needed crutches to walk around. He was also wearing a boot. "I guess I'm day to day," Carter said. Earlier in the game, Toronto rookie center Chris Bosh re-sprained his left ankle and didn't return. Bosh missed three games earlier this month because of the injury, and left Toronto's previous game against Seattle after aggravating it. He's listed as day to day. "It's a nagging injury that won't go away," Bosh said. "It's frustrating. I'm tired of sitting out games. I'm tired of being bored before the game." The Raptors are already missing Jalen Rose, who will miss at least a month with four broken bones in his left hand. Charlie Ward's open 3-pointer gave San Antonio a 72-71 lead with 4:13 left -- the Spurs' first lead since the second quarter. After Duncan missed a layup, Malik Rose grabbed the rebound and converted a three-point play to make it a four-point game. Toronto's Morris Peterson followed with a 3-pointer and Alvin Williams made a jumper to give Toronto the lead again, but Duncan made two free throws with 1:36 remaining. Williams followed with a layup, but Hedo Turkoglu's 3-pointer gave San Antonio a two-point lead with 1:01 remaining. Duncan's hook shot made it 82-78 with 23 seconds left. Milt Palacio's layup cut it to two with 15 seconds left, but Ward made two free throws with 11.6 remaining and Manu Ginobili made two more with 5.3 seconds left. "Obviously, due to their misfortune we got a big break at the end of the game," San Antonio coach Gregg Popovich said. "I sure hope Vince is OK. You never like to see a player get carried off. That was probably the difference in the game; we didn't have anybody to guard him." San Antonio outrebounded Toronto 58-39. Duncan previously had 21 rebounds this season on Oct. 29 at Denver. Both teams had complaints with the officials in the first half. Popovich received a technical foul for arguing that Carter had his foot on the 3-point line in the first quarter. Kevin O'Neill received one for arguing about a non-call on Morris Peterson, and Carter got one after screaming at official Ed Malloy after Malloy called an offensive foul on him. The officials were booed when they left the court at halftime and when they returned for the second half.

Game notes
San Antonio beat Toronto 73-70 the last time they played. ... Toronto forward Robert Archibald air-balled a free throw in the first half. The crowd erupted when he made his next one. ... Bosh, the fourth overall pick in last April's draft, is averaging 11.0 points and 7.4 rebounds.
